#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:-1
msgid ""
"A guide to creating custom build systems in Spack for packaging software "
"with its own build scripts or adding support for new build systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:13
msgid "Custom Build Systems"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:15
msgid ""
"While the built-in build systems should meet your needs for the vast "
"majority of packages, some packages provide custom build scripts. This guide "
"is intended for the following use cases:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:18
msgid "Packaging software with its own custom build system"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:19
msgid "Adding support for new build systems"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:21
msgid ""
"If you want to add support for a new build system, a good place to start is "
"to look at the definitions of other build systems. This guide focuses mostly "
"on how Spack's build systems work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:24
msgid ""
"In this guide, we will be using the `perl <https://github.com/spack/spack-"
"packages/blob/develop/repos/spack_repo/builtin/packages/perl/package.py>`_ "
"and `cmake <https://github.com/spack/spack-packages/blob/develop/repos/"
"spack_repo/builtin/packages/cmake/package.py>`_ packages as examples. "
"``perl``'s build system is a hand-written ``Configure`` shell script, while "
"``cmake`` bootstraps itself during installation. Both of these packages "
"require custom build systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:29
msgid "Base class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:31
msgid ""
"If your package does not belong to any of the built-in build systems that "
"Spack already supports, you should inherit from the ``Package`` base class. "
"``Package`` is a simple base class with a single phase: ``install``. If your "
"package is simple, you may be able to simply write an ``install`` method "
"that gets the job done. However, if your package is more complex and "
"installation involves multiple steps, you should add separate phases as "
"mentioned in the next section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:36
msgid ""
"If you are creating a new build system base class, you should inherit from "
"``PackageBase``. This is the superclass for all build systems in Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:40
msgid "Phases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:42
msgid ""
"The most important concept in Spack's build system support is the idea of "
"phases. Each build system defines a set of phases that are necessary to "
"install the package. They usually follow some sort of \"configure\", "
"\"build\", \"install\" guideline, but any of those phases may be missing or "
"combined with another phase."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:46
msgid "If you look at the ``perl`` package, you'll see:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:48
msgid "phases = (\"configure\", \"build\", \"install\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:52
msgid "Similarly, ``cmake`` defines:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:54
msgid "phases = (\"bootstrap\", \"build\", \"install\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:58
msgid ""
"If we look at the ``cmake`` example, this tells Spack's ``PackageBase`` "
"class to run the ``bootstrap``, ``build``, and ``install`` functions in that "
"order. It is now up to you to define these methods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:62
msgid "Phase and phase_args functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:64
msgid "If we look at ``perl``, we see that it defines a ``configure`` method:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:66
msgid ""
"def configure(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    configure = Executable(\"./Configure\")\n"
"    configure(*self.configure_args())"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:72
msgid ""
"There is also a corresponding ``configure_args`` function that handles all "
"of the arguments to pass to ``Configure``, just like in "
"``AutotoolsPackage``. Comparatively, the ``build`` and ``install`` phases "
"are pretty simple:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:75
msgid ""
"def build(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    make()\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def install(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    make(\"install\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:84
msgid ""
"The ``cmake`` package looks very similar, but with a ``bootstrap`` function "
"instead of ``configure``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:86
msgid ""
"def bootstrap(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    bootstrap = Executable(\"./bootstrap\")\n"
"    bootstrap(*self.bootstrap_args())\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def build(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    make()\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def install(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    make(\"install\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:100
msgid ""
"Again, there is a ``bootstrap_args`` function that determines the correct "
"bootstrap flags to use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:103
msgid "``run_before`` / ``run_after``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:105
msgid ""
"Occasionally, you may want to run extra steps either before or after a given "
"phase. This applies not just to custom build systems, but to existing build "
"systems as well. You may need to patch a file that is generated by "
"configure, or install extra files in addition to what ``make install`` "
"copies to the installation prefix. This is where ``@run_before`` and "
"``@run_after`` come in."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:110
msgid ""
"These Python decorators allow you to write functions that are called before "
"or after a particular phase. For example, in ``perl``, we see:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:113
msgid ""
"@run_after(\"install\")\n"
"def install_cpanm(self):\n"
"    spec = self.spec\n"
"    maker = make\n"
"    cpan_dir = join_path(\"cpanm\", \"cpanm\")\n"
"    if sys.platform == \"win32\":\n"
"        maker = nmake\n"
"        cpan_dir = join_path(self.stage.source_path, cpan_dir)\n"
"        cpan_dir = windows_sfn(cpan_dir)\n"
"    if \"+cpanm\" in spec:\n"
"        with working_dir(cpan_dir):\n"
"            perl = spec[\"perl\"].command\n"
"            perl(\"Makefile.PL\")\n"
"            maker()\n"
"            maker(\"install\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:131
msgid ""
"This extra step automatically installs ``cpanm`` in addition to the base "
"Perl installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:134
msgid "``on_package_attributes``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:136
msgid ""
"The ``run_before`` / ``run_after`` logic discussed above becomes "
"particularly powerful when combined with the ``@on_package_attributes`` "
"decorator. This decorator allows you to conditionally run certain functions "
"depending on the attributes of that package. The most common example is "
"conditional testing. Many unit tests are prone to failure, even when there "
"is nothing wrong with the installation. Unfortunately, non-portable unit "
"tests and tests that are \"supposed to fail\" are more common than we would "
"like. Instead of always running unit tests on installation, Spack lets users "
"conditionally run tests with the ``--test=root`` flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:143
msgid ""
"If we wanted to define a function that would conditionally run if and only "
"if this flag is set, we would use the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:145
msgid ""
"@on_package_attributes(run_tests=True)\n"
"def my_test_function(self): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:151
msgid "Testing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:153
msgid ""
"Let's put everything together and add unit tests to be optionally run during "
"the installation of our package. In the ``perl`` package, we can see:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:156
msgid ""
"@run_after(\"build\")\n"
"@on_package_attributes(run_tests=True)\n"
"def build_test(self):\n"
"    if sys.platform == \"win32\":\n"
"        win32_dir = os.path.join(self.stage.source_path, \"win32\")\n"
"        win32_dir = windows_sfn(win32_dir)\n"
"        with working_dir(win32_dir):\n"
"            nmake(\"test\", ignore_quotes=True)\n"
"    else:\n"
"        make(\"test\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:169
msgid ""
"As you can guess, this runs ``make test`` *after* building the package, if "
"and only if testing is requested. Again, this is not specific to custom "
"build systems, it can be added to existing build systems as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:174
msgid "The order of decorators matters. The following ordering:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:177
msgid ""
"@run_after(\"install\")\n"
"@on_package_attributes(run_tests=True)\n"
"def my_test_function(self): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:183
msgid "works as expected. However, if you reverse the ordering:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:186
msgid ""
"@on_package_attributes(run_tests=True)\n"
"@run_after(\"install\")\n"
"def my_test_function(self): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:192
msgid ""
"the tests will always be run regardless of whether or not ``--test=root`` is "
"requested. See https://github.com/spack/spack/issues/3833 for more "
"information"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:195
msgid ""
"Ideally, every package in Spack will have some sort of test to ensure that "
"it was built correctly. It is up to the package authors to make sure this "
"happens. If you are adding a package for some software and the developers "
"list commands to test the installation, please add these tests to your "
"``package.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/custompackage.rst:199
msgid ""
"For more information on other forms of package testing, refer to :ref:"
"`Checking an installation <checking_an_installation>`."
msgstr ""
